---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SEOHead from '../../components/SEOHead.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';
import BlogSchema from "../../components/BlogSchema.astro";
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import FAQSchema from '../../components/FAQSchema.astro';

const TITLE = "Tattoo Healing Issues: Normal Healing vs Infection";
const DESC = "Itching and peeling are normal. Spreading redness, streaks, pus, or fever are not. Learn the difference and exactly what to do at each stage.";
const URL = "https://ink-flows.com/blog/aftercare-issues";
---

<BaseLayout pageTitle="Tattoo Healing Issues">
  <BlogSchema title={TITLE} description={DESC} publishedDate="2026-07-18" author="Sarah Chen" image="/images/blog/aftercare-guide.svg" tags={["infected tattoo", "tattoo healing problems", "tattoo infection signs"]} />
  <SEOHead slot="head" title={TITLE} description={DESC} />
  <Navbar />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://ink-flows.com/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Blog", "item": "https://ink-flows.com/blog" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Tattoo Healing Issues", "item": URL }
    ]
  })} />

  <article class="pt-24 pb-16 sm:pt-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-4" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-accent-400">Home</a> <span class="mx-1">/</span>
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-accent-400">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">/</span>
        <a href="/blog/tattoo-aftercare-guide" class="hover:text-accent-400">Aftercare</a> <span class="mx-1">/</span>
        <span class="text-gray-400">Issues</span>
      </nav>
      <p class="text-sm text-accent-400 mb-4">July 18, 2026</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-white sm:text-4xl">Tattoo Healing Issues: Normal Healing vs Infection</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-gray-300">
        Most "is this normal?" moments are just healing. But some signs mean stop and get help. Here's the line between normal and a problem — and what to do at each stage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="border-t border-ink-800/50 py-12">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 prose prose-invert">

      <h2>Normal healing signs</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Redness (day 1–3):</strong> mild, fades within a few days.</li>
        <li><strong>Itch:</strong> peaks around day 4–8 as it flakes — don't scratch.</li>
        <li><strong>Peeling / flaking:</strong> like a sunburn, often tinted with color.</li>
        <li><strong>Cloudiness:</strong> the tattoo looks a bit milky before lines sharpen.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Infection warning signs</h2>
      <p>These go beyond normal and need a clinician, not a forum:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Spreading redness</strong> that grows past the tattoo edge after day 3</li>
        <li><strong>Red streaks</strong> running from the tattoo up a limb</li>
        <li><strong>Yellow or green pus</strong>, or a hot, throbbing area</li>
        <li><strong>Fever, chills, or swollen lymph nodes</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you see any of these, contact a healthcare provider. The <a href="https://www.aad.org/public/everyday-care/skin-care-basics/tattoos/tattoo-aftercare" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">AAD</a> and <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/tattoos/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">NHS</a> both advise seeking care for signs of infection rather than waiting.</p>

      <h2>Blowout during healing</h2>
      <p>A blowout (ink blurred under the skin) is a placement issue, not aftercare — it won't heal away. If lines look spread or "fuzzy" once healed, go back to your artist about a touch-up or correction. This is separate from normal peeling.</p>

      <h2>Allergic reaction</h2>
      <p>A rash <em>outside</em> the tattoo outline, or a reaction to the adhesive (second skin) rather than the ink, is an allergy signal. Stop the product, wash the area, and check with a clinician if it spreads or itches severely.</p>

      <h2>What to do at each stage</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Photo-log daily:</strong> a quick photo in the same light shows change over time.</li>
        <li><strong>Message your artist:</strong> they know your skin and technique — send the photo.</li>
        <li><strong>See a doctor</strong> if you have any infection warning sign above.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>About this guide</h2>
      <p>Written by <strong>Sarah Chen</strong>, Founder &amp; CEO at InkFlow. Sources: <a href="https://www.aad.org/public/everyday-care/skin-care-basics/tattoos/tattoo-aftercare" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">American Academy of Dermatology</a> and <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/tattoos/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">NHS</a>. Companion to the <a href="/blog/tattoo-aftercare-guide" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">full tattoo aftercare guide</a>. Published July 18, 2026.</p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <h3>Can small tattoos peel?</h3>
      <p>Yes — size doesn't change the process. A small tattoo peels just like a large one, often in a tighter area.</p>
      <h3>Is a yellow scab on a tattoo infected?</h3>
      <p>Not always — a little plasma-yellow crust early on is normal. Yellow <em>pus</em> with heat, spreading redness, or fever is infection. When in doubt, get it checked.</p>
      <h3>Can a tattoo heal without second skin?</h3>
      <p>Absolutely. Wash-and-lotion aftercare has been the standard for decades and heals fine without any film.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FAQSchema
    questions={[
      { question: "Can small tattoos peel during healing?", answer: "Yes. Size does not change the healing process — a small tattoo peels just like a large one." },
      { question: "Is a yellow scab on a tattoo a sign of infection?", answer: "Not always. A little plasma-yellow crust early on is normal. Yellow pus with heat, spreading redness, or fever is infection — get it checked." },
      { question: "Can a tattoo heal without second skin?", answer: "Yes. Wash-and-lotion aftercare has been the standard for decades and heals fine without any film." },
    ]}
  />

  <section class="py-16 text-center border-t border-ink-800/50">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Back to the main guide</h2>
      <a href="/blog/tattoo-aftercare-guide" class="mt-6 inline-block rounded-lg bg-accent-500 px-8 py-3.5 text-base font-semibold text-ink-950 hover:bg-accent-400 transition-all">Read the full aftercare guide →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
